{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17525264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17525264"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:14:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14070"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14070"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.61,0.16,0.11,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55598"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6729"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41138"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"1284"},{"type":"tags","id":"1875"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2664"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14272"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16761"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43473"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55598"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old Indigenous woman presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up of chronic kidney disease. She has a medical history of hypertension, type 2 diabetes mellitus and a mechanical aortic valve as a consequence of rheumatic heart disease. Her regular medications are metformin 1000 mg twice daily (immediate release), linagliptin 5 mg daily, perindopril 10 mg daily and warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 138/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. On cardiovascular examination, a mechanical click is audible without any murmurs. She weighs 60Kg. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal worsening kidney function compared to her previous appointment. The most recent results are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR): 48 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E (\u0026gt;90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine albumin-to-creatinine ratio: 70 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine clearance: 42 mL/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Change to metformin 2000 mg daily (extended release) and change warfarin to enoxaparin","Reduce metformin to 500 mg twice daily (immediate release) and continue warfarin","Reduce metformin to 500 mg twice daily (immediate release) and change warfarin to enoxaparin","Discontinue metformin and continue warfarin","Discontinue metformin and change warfarin to rivaroxaban"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis Indigenous patient presents with worsening chronic kidney disease (CKD) in the context of type 2 diabetes mellitus and a mechanical aortic valve. The most appropriate management plan involves adjusting her medications based on her current renal function while considering her other comorbidities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing metformin to 500 mg twice daily (immediate release) and continuing warfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management plan. Metformin dose adjustment is necessary when eGFR falls below 60 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Australian guidelines recommend a \u003Cem\u003Etotal\u003C/em\u003E maximum daily dose of 2000 mg for patients with a GFR of 60\u201390 mL/min, and 1000 mg for patients with a GFR of 30\u201360 mL/min.\u003Ca class=\u0022hash-changer\u0022 href=\u0022https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/january-february/prescribing-for-older-people-with-cri#ref-15\u0022\u003E\u003Csup\u003E \u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/a\u003EMetformin is not recommended for patients with a GFR \u0026lt;30 mL/min. Some guidelines, use CrCl as a reference measure for metformin dosing. Clinicians should reference local guidelines and discuss with pharmacists as required. Continuing warfarin is crucial for patients with mechanical heart valves, regardless of kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChanging to metformin 2000 mg daily (extended release) and changing warfarin to enoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate, as there has been no \u003Cem\u003Etotal\u003C/em\u003E dose change to the patient\u0027s metformin, and enoxaparin (a subcutaneous injection) is not suitable for long-term anticoagulation in patients with mechanical heart valves. There is no need to change warfarin even if kidney function is declining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing metformin to 500 mg twice daily (immediate release) and changing warfarin to enoxaparin\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because enoxaparin (a subcutaneous injection) is not suitable for long-term anticoagulation in patients with mechanical heart valves. There is no need to change warfarin even if kidney function is declining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinuing metformin and continuing warfarin\u003C/strong\u003E is overly cautious at this stage. While metformin should be discontinued when eGFR falls below 30 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, this patient\u0027s eGFR is still above this threshold. Dose reduction is more appropriate than complete discontinuation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiscontinuing metformin and changing warfarin to rivaroxaban\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While metformin should be discontinued when eGFR falls below 30 mL/min/1.73m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, this patient\u0027s eGFR is still above this threshold. Dose reduction is more appropriate than complete discontinuation. This patient should be continued on warfarin, which (for now), remains the standard anticoagulation of choice for patients with mechanical heart valves.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing CKD in Indigenous patients, it is important to consider cultural factors that may influence medical care. Regular monitoring of renal function, adjustment of medications as needed, involvement of Aboriginal Liaison Officers and interpreters where appropriate, and a holistic approach to care are crucial.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Metformin dose should be reduced when eGFR falls below 60 mL/min/1.73m2 and discontinued when it falls below 30 mL/min/1.73m2.","Warfarin remains the anticoagulant of choice for patients with mechanical heart valves, regardless of kidney function."],"references":["Prescribing for older people with chronic renal impairment [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. 2013. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/january-february/prescribing-for-older-people-with-cri"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41138"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14070"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41138","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41138"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-16T22:25:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-16T22:25:55+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":